Europe
------
[1] Russia (Chelyabinsk oblast)
Date: 8 Nov 2013
Source: Novii Region 2 [in Russian, trans. Mod.CP, edited]
http://www.nr2.ru/chel/469392.html


Outbreaks of measles virus infection have been reported from 3 municipalities in the Chelyabinsk Region. The 1st measles case was reported in October 2013 in Korkino. According to Novii Regio, the Regional Epidemiology Authorities as of today [8 Nov 2013] have recorded 55 cases of measles. In Troitsk during September-October 2013, a total of 46 people became ill, including 39 children aged 7 months to 17 years. 11 of those infected had been vaccinated against measles, and 9 were diagnosed in September 2013 within 72 hours of the detection of the 1st cases.

The measles outbreak in Troitsk began among the Roma population, and now the infection has spread to other communities. In addition to the Troitsk outbreak, measles has now been recorded in Korkino. In October 2013, 4 people, 3 of them were Roma children, became infected. The youngest patient was one month old at the time of diagnosis. In Chelyabinsk [city], 3 children who came with their parents from Kyrgyzstan fell ill with measles. Then, 3 of their relatives (a woman and her 3 children) and some health-care workers became ill. The children had not been vaccinated. According to epidemiologists, one in 4 measles patients is more severely infected than the others. 14 people have been hospitalised in the infectious department. In 4 of the children, measles was complicated by pneumonia.

Currently, medical surveillance is in progress to identify contacts and to vaccinate those not already vaccinated. So far, 640 children and 1000 adults have been vaccinated. However, not all those in contact with the patients have agreed to be vaccinated.

The last outbreak of measles in the South Urals occurred in 2006. Measles infection is dangerous because of its complications, which include severe pneumonia, otitis media [middle ear infection], meningitis, and encephalitis. Measles remains a major cause of death among young children worldwide. It is estimated that in 2011, measles killed 158 000 people, most of them children under the age of 5 years. Immunization against measles is the only effective defense against the infection. In the Chelyabinsk region, over 2400 children aged 2 to 17 years old have not been vaccinated against measles, mainly due to the intransigence of their parents, and 6500 adults aged up to 35 years have still to be vaccinated according to the national schedule.

[Byline: Julia Maletskaya]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[As elsewhere in Russia, recent outbreaks of measles, mainly in border areas, are being attributed to migration of unvaccinated communities into these regions of Russia. Previously, Russia has had a good record in containment of measles virus infection.

A map of the Chelyabinsk Region can be accessed at: http://russiaprofile.org/bg_places/resources_territory_districts_chelyabinsk.html. - Mod.CP

