[3] Ukraine (Kiev)
Date: Wed 13 Nov 2013
Source: ForUm [in Russian, trans. Mod.CP, edited]
http://for-ua.com/ukraine/2013/11/13/153330.html


A measles epidemic in Ukraine is not imminent, according to the Director of the Institute of Epidemiology and Infectious Diseases. "The peak of the last epidemic occurred in 2012. Now, we are seeing the so-called "tail" of the recovery. This will persist up to the end of this year [2013] and most likely into the following winter, due to the usual seasonal increased morbidity," stated aid Zadorozhnaja.

According to the specialist, measles is a cyclical disease, which means that there is a so-called epidemic phase, when the incidence increases dramatically. "The last 2 occurred in 2000-2002 and 2005-2006, and another rise began in late 2011 that has not yet ended. It peaked in 2012, when measles affected more than 12 000 people," she said.

Zadorozhnaja also noted that today the main problem in the fight against measles is the low level of immunisation. "Prior to 2005-2007, the level of coverage was more than 95 percent, and this year [2013] so far, it is about 30 percent, and in Kiev it is only a little over 50 percent. In this case, the threat of an epidemic according to experts begins when the vaccination rate falls below 90 percent.

According to the ForUm news agency, between 23 Oct and 8 Nov 2013, there was an outbreak of measles in the Tseptsevichi Sarnensky area affecting stage I-III students at a secondary school, which, as of 8 Nov 2013, had affected 53 children. All the patients had a mild form of the disease.

[Byline: Valentina Dudka]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The attitude of the Ukrainian Health Authorities seems rather complacent in view of the fact that uptake of vaccine in Kiev City has fallen from 95 percent to 50 percent. The reason for this decline remains unexplained. Further information would be appreciated.

Maps of Ukraine can be accessed at: http://www.russia-ukraine-travel.com/ukraine-maps.html. - Mod.CP

