[4] UK (Wales)
Date: Wed 13 Nov 2013
Source: The Yorkshire Post [edited]
http://www.yorkshirepost.co.uk/news/main-topics/general-news/report-identifies-source-of-massive-measles-outbreak-1-6239242


Four children who visited a holiday camp in England caught measles and later caused an epidemic which infected more than 1200 people. The insight into the measles outbreak which swept across an area of Wales last winter [2012-13] is contained in a new report into the epidemic which was published yesterday [12 Nov 2013]. The report makes 13 separate recommendations which together are designed to stop the spread of the disease in future. It also reveals that the epidemic, which took 8 months to stamp out and claimed one life, consisted of 4 separate simultaneous outbreaks.

The report calls for an aggressive drive to stamp out measles in Wales and recommends launching a campaign to target still unprotected teenagers. It suggests using sexual health clinics to deliver the triple measles, mumps and rubella (MMR) vaccination to those who remain unprotected. But it warns that with more than 30 000 people aged 10 to 18 still unvaccinated, new outbreaks of the potentially deadly virus could occur.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[It is unclear why uptake of vaccination in the 10-to-18-year-old population remains stubbornly so low despite the wide provision of supplementary vaccination. - Mod.CP

