The Americas
-------------
[5] Canada (Alberta)
Date: 13 Wed 13 Nov 2013
Source: Global News [edited]
http://globalnews.ca/news/960150/vaccination-clinics-added-amid-measles-outbreak/


As of Wednesday morning [14 Nov 2013], there are 28 cases of measles confirmed in the province, and Alberta Health Services (AHS) is turning its attention to 2 new communities in hopes of containing the outbreak. Vaccination clinics have been set up in 2 Hills and Lacombe for children aged 6 months to 17 years old and for those aged 4-17 who have not had a 2nd dose of the measles vaccine.

The Chief Medical Officer of AHS told Global News that the outbreak is expected to spread from the South Zone communities of Coaldale and Fort Macleod to other low immunization communities. "We know that in the south, there are a number of communities that have ties -- and they're low immunisation rates -- and they have ties with other areas of the province," explained Dr. Martin Lavoie. "Depending on how low those rates are, how close the ties are, we're expecting a spread from the south. It's just a matter of time to spread from there to those other low immunization communities."

Both post-secondary institutions in Lethbridge have confirmed they are working with AHS to inform students of the extremely contagious virus before they head home for the holidays.

[Byline: Tamara Elliott]

