[6] Australia (Victoria) travel alert
Date: Tue 12 Nov 2013
Source: The Sydney Morning Herald [edited]
http://www.smh.com.au/travel/travel-incidents/measles-cases-linked-to-time-in-bali-20131112-2xdcn.html


Five Victorians have been diagnosed with measles after returning from Bali over the past 5 weeks, prompting warnings for people to be vaccinated before travelling to Indonesia. Victoria's acting chief health officer Michael Ackland said the 5 people diagnosed following their travels had passed on the disease to a further 3 people in Victoria. Dr Ackland said young people who had not been vaccinated were most at risk of contracting measles, as well as adults aged between 33 and 47, because many people in that age group had not been vaccinated as children. He said doctors should recommend 2 doses of measles vaccine to patients planning to travel to Bali who had not previously had measles or been vaccinated. If patients were travelling within the next month, they should have one dose before departure and a 2nd dose upon return to Australia, he said.

Measles is a highly infectious viral disease that can cause serious illness including pneumonia, with people diagnosed often requiring treatment in hospital. Dr Ackland said measles usually began with common cold symptoms including fever, sore throat, red eyes and a cough. A rash usually begins 3 to 7 days after the 1st symptoms, often starting on the face and then spreading to the rest of the body.

